MS";padding-bottom:0pt;page-break-after:avoid}</style></head><body class="c6"><p class="c2"><span>Lead,
which they called &ldquo;plumbum&rdquo;, was widely used in Roman
times and has been around for thousands of years. They used lead to
make pipes, writing tablets, and coins. They also used it to make pots
and pans, which later caused lead poisoning.</span></p><p class="c0
c4"><span></span></p><p class="c2"><span>It is a natural element, but
it is rarely found as a pure element. Instead it is most commonly
found in ores of lead sulfide (galena). It is isolated by being
smelted which converts the ore to the compound of lead oxide. The lead
oxide is then heated with pure carbon which isolates the lead. The
formula looks like this:</span></p><p class="c0
c4"><span></span></p><p class="c5"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;PbO</span><span class="c3">2</span><span>+C--heated&rarr;CO</span><span class="c3">2</span><span>+Pb</span></p><p class="c0"><span></span></p><p class="c5"><span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Lead&rsquo;s
boiling point is approximately 1750&deg;C, its melting point is
372.46&deg;C, its density is 11.34 grams per
cm</span><span class="c1">3</span><span>, and its hardness is marked
at 1.5 Mohs. It is solid at room temperature, it is gray colored, it
has 82 protons and 4 valence
electrons.</span></p><p class="c0"><span></span></p><p class="c2"><span>Lead
use was decreased when the effects of lead poisoning were
understood. &nbsp;For example, it was used in ammunition, sheet lead
(used in building construction), solder, piping for water and sewage,
ball bearings, radiation shielding, and as a gasoline
additive.</span></p><p class="c0
c4"><span></span></p><p class="c2"><span>No one is sure how lead got
its English name, but its chemical symbol comes from its Roman
name. &nbsp;Pure lead is priced at $2.45 for 100 grams, $11 a
pound. It can cause immediate and long-term health problems,
especially with children.</span></p></body></html>
